data.content:
Yes — there are two better approaches depending on your MSTest version:

**1. Use `[DataRow]` for simple inline data:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Use tuples with `DynamicData` (MSTest 3.x+) for type safety:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**`DataRow`** is simplest for compile-time constants. **Tuples** are better when you need computed values or complex types — you get type safety without the `object[]` boxing and casting risks.
